comments.textDisplay: Well this review is not surprising at all. La Llorona doesn't haunt houses. The fact that the movie happens in a house is stupid by itself. They could've had the family vacationing or camping near a river in the woods, for accuracy's sake. And they should've filmed in a Latin country. And if it was too expensive, then film in Puerto Rico. We have that legend too! (And if they didn't want the country to be PR, we're basically stand-in for every freaking country imaginable for Hollywood, so it wouldn't matter). It sounds like this movie was a total wasted opportunity. And probably reason that a Latino director should make the movie instead.

comments.textDisplay: Jeremy talking about the umbrella‚Äî that actually happened to me. I remember one night when I was very young, probably eight or nine, (I lived in a very small town) I was walking from my uncle‚Äôs house to my aunt‚Äôs house ...my aunt was with me and it was just a few blocks from one house to the other (it was dark) it had started to rain, as we walked, right in the corner, next to the light pole I saw this woman wearing all white, impassively, with a blank stare, pale, alone,  I would dare to say she was even glowing. Her eyes, as dark as the night, her stare, I felt the blood rushing down my spine, and my lips numb with fear, we kept walking but now at a different pace, I could feel my aunts hand embracing mine tighter. The woman, there, under the light... and then the wind hit our umbrella with a gust as it covered our line of sight just for a few seconds, maybe one or two, and when my aunt managed to pull the umbrella back up  the woman wasn‚Äôt there anymore, my aunt claimed to her God. We looked around, nothing... We rushed home, and my aunt started praying the Rosary and Hail Marys And that was 20 years ago.
